{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:56:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:56:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16757"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0,0.04,0.89,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76217"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61721"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9830"},{"type":"tags","id":"9871"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22339"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76217"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPlasma proteins are essential molecules in blood that help maintain fluid balance between different body compartments. The total plasma protein concentration is typically 60-80 g/L, with albumin being the most abundant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of plasma proteins in maintaining fluid balance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Create hydrostatic pressure within vessels","Buffer changes in blood osmolality","Facilitate passive diffusion across capillaries","Generate oncotic pressure to retain fluid in vessels","Regulate capillary membrane permeability"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate oncotic pressure to retain fluid in vessels\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of plasma proteins in fluid balance. Plasma proteins, particularly albumin which contributes about 75% of the effect, create oncotic (colloid osmotic) pressure that opposes hydrostatic pressure and helps keep fluid within the vascular space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreate hydrostatic pressure within vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - Hydrostatic pressure is generated by cardiac contraction and blood vessel tone, not by plasma proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuffer changes in blood osmolality\u003C/strong\u003E - While proteins have some buffering capacity, this is not their primary role in fluid balance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitate passive diffusion across capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteins actually help retain fluid within vessels rather than facilitating its movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulate capillary membrane permeability\u003C/strong\u003E - Plasma proteins do not directly control membrane permeability\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe oncotic pressure generated by plasma proteins (approximately 25 mmHg) helps maintain appropriate intravascular volume by counteracting hydrostatic pressure that would otherwise force fluid out of the vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Plasma proteins maintain oncotic pressure which helps retain fluid within blood vessels.","Albumin is the most abundant plasma protein and contributes about 75% of plasma oncotic pressure.","The total protein concentration in plasma is typically 60-80 g/L."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61721"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61721"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:12:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:13:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76217"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovasc